previous: >>29297977

Goal of the thread: Go out for a walk, or try to get any other form of small exercise (walking stairs for 5 mins for example)
Daily goals can be repeated. Remember to keep score, it can only go up!

>What is this thread for?
Getting better is hard, and sucks. A lot. It does not get easier doing it alone.
Share resources and experiences with combating depression, anxiety, personal issues, achieving or maintaining a healthy weight, etc.
>Why is this thread /lgbt/?
Struggles with mental and physical health are an indisputable part of /lgbt/ life, be it from dysphoria, social pressure, heartbreak, or just unfortunate lifestyle choices.
>Notes to consider:
Please be civil. Shame is your greatest enemy in fighting urges of self abuse (be it sh, drugs, or just self deprecation). Relapsing into bad and unhealthy habits is to be expected, the goal is to increase the average amount of time it takes between relapses. Any improvement is a victory no matter how small. Your worth and right to get better are non-negotiable. And most importantly:
WE ARE NOT THERAPISTS, WE DON'T REPLACE MEDICATION
>Note on advice
Generic advice won't necessarily help you in particular, but for those it does it is an essential foundation to build future progress on, not a miracle cure. Do not underestimate the effects subtle changes to your lifestyle can have. Try first, keep us posted on your progress, build from there.

We are *always* short on self help resources, so if anything was useful to you, let us know!
Since the OP is getting too long I moved all resources into their own post, see below!

They're what allow us to look each other in the eyes and feel the knowledge that there is nothing else in the universe like us.
Being alive is hard. I don't know if I would have chosen it if I had gotten the chance to decide from the start, weighing it against the collective weight of all the suffering I'd ever feel. But God, I love so many things about *living*. The sound of birds chirping or a waterfall rushing in the woods, the smile on a friend's face when you crack a joke. The knowledge that though our lives may all be stitched together from the same joys and the same pains I will be the only one to ever experience a moment in the way I do until the end of time. A lot of the time it hurts, and I don't think it hurts for any sort of big cosmic reason that makes everything click into place. But to hurt is part of what it means to be human.

posts.name: Anonymous
posts.com:
>>29273969
Taking extra T to boost your T probably won't have the effects you desire beyond the short term. Spare T metabolises into E2, and E2 shuts down your T production. What will happen is you get a week or two of high T, which fades into slightly high T and elevated E, which then fades back to your normal T levels as your body stabilises around the steroids you're taking. You'd basically have to ramp up and replace your natural production entirely with supplemental T, and then you're still going to end up with elevated E (which is why steroid users grow boobs).

Your natural T production isn't determined by how much T there is in your blood, they're determined by how much E2 there is in your blood. Leftover T turns into E2. If you have a naturally low T level, that means your androgen receptors just aren't using more T than that, because enough T is left over to tell your testicles to ramp down. Barring things like damage to the testicles or hypothyroidism I don't know anything about, your blood will probably have as much T as your body needs.

I recommend you not play with steroids, and just get your body in shape with discipline and hard work. A good exercise regime will not only stabilise your circadian rhythm, making it easier to sleep properly, but it will also increase your body's androgen receptiveness, boosting how much T you can make use of, and thus also boosting how much T your body will produce. It'll also produce a lot of serotonin, which is basically a "feel good" hormone.

It's anecdotal. Might be true, might not be. Basically, when you swallow E2, either as a whole pill or as part of your saliva if you're doing sublingual, it will go through your liver and metabolise into estrone, which some think plays a role in cis puberty breast development.

Plenty of trannies who have done E2 monotherapy from day one and grown big tits too, so it's dubious there's a benefit. Powers suggests that oral E can help "reboot" stalled breast development, but that's still anecdotal.

Valerate is better than straight E2, but enanthate is better than valerate. It's about half lives. Enanthate has twice the half life valerate does, which means it's way less spiky. Valerate is usually one injection per week, and the curve for that is as bad as enanthate once every other week. I recommend enanthate weekly, you get a smooth curve, which means no risk of PMS.

Try doing intermittent fasting. I eat the same size meals as I did before, but only once a day. Ie, instead of breakfast, lunch, and dinner, I just eat a bigass dinner. It's called a daily 24 hour fast, or sometimes "warrior diet", though that involves a lot of stuff I don't do, like stuffing yourself with cereal and peanuts.
Basically, within eight hours of eating a meal, your body is in food mode, and will get nutrients by burning the food you ate. After eight hours, you switch into burning fat mode. Most people are only in burning fat mode for a few hours a day, but I'm in it sixteen hours a day. I'm not even eating healthy food or exercising, I'm just as lazy as before, but I'm losing weight at a crazy rate. I've never been able to lose weight by dieting before, because I just feel constantly hungry and end up eating bigger portions instead, but now that I can eat a full size meal I don't have that problem anymore. I enter burning fat mode during the night, so I don't even feel particularly hungry in the morning.

Just make sure you stop doing it once you're thin. When you run out of fat your body will start burning muscle instead.

>>29304761
Bica doesn't shut down your T production, it just stops your androgen receptors from binding to it.
I guess maybe as your bica levels wore off, your T levels were high enough to cause remasculation? Mono E doesn't stop your T production immediately, so it's possible you had a week or two where your bica level was low enough to reactivate your androgen receptors, while your T production hadn't yet dropped too low to matter.
You should maybe get back on the bica a while? Just speculating here.

Also, it's not uncommon to get temporary hair loss when switching between spiro, duta, fina, etc. Possibly the same thing applies to bica. The hair will grow back, it's just that the switch in hormone levels fucked with the growth cycle of the follicle.

Aye, be aware that miniaturized hairs sit higher in the skin, so you won't need as much depth as people suggest initially. Scalp skin will be thinner too unless you've been on E with nuked T/DHT for a while.
https://www.sciencedirect.com/science/article/pii/S0022202X15529400
>Vellus hairs are inconspicuous and are 0.03 mm or less in diameter and less than 1 cm in length and lack melanin and medulla. Terminal hairs miniaturized to vellus hair proportions are termed vellus-like hairs. Terminal hairs are rooted in subcutaneous tissue or deep dermis. Vellus hairs are rooted in upper dermis.
0.6mm seems to be a good depth, there's a study comparing it to 1.2mm where it was deemed superior, and the original study suggested a cyclical split between 0.25/0.5mm (this is with a roller though, and in mice on their body).
https://pubmed.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/32897622/
https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pmc/articles/PMC5064188/
I personally needle every 3 weeks, I was doing 1.2mm but I'm moving to 0.6mm next time I do it to see if it makes a difference. I use a Dr. Pen w/11 pin carts.

>vials
*vial
They last long enough that you should only need to bring one. Put it in your bag with other toiletries in your luggage and it'll probably pass the xray unremarked, looking just like a bottle of lotion, or a bottle of insulin to an AI/someone competent.
What might set them off is bringing needles. Check the country you're travelling to, odds are you can pick up insulin syringes without a prescription at a pharmacy, that would be the safest option.

If you know someone with diabetes, ask if you can steal the label off one of their insulin bottles. You could put that on your estrogen vial for extra safety. Pack needles also if you're doing this. 10ml vials all look the same and diabetes is too common for them to bother asking for a prescription slip. If you do this you should bring the vial and the needles in your purse as hand luggage, to better pass as a diabetic.

Also, don't panic if they do take your estrogen. Just shoot up before you get to the airport. Assuming you're on enanthate, you'll miss your dosage by two weeks, but all that will happen is menopause, two weeks without E isn't enough to remasculate. Hot flashes aren't exactly pleasant, but they won't kill you.
